גמ’ השתא בשלוחו מקדש בו מיבעיא:
< גמ’ השתא בשלוחו מקדש בו מיבעיא <gray>אמר
< רב יוסף מצוה בו יותר מבשלוחו כי הא דרב</gray>
Let’s bring in a few pieces of background info and use it to understand this line of the Gemara.
1) The Aramaic word השתא, _hashta_, has a special meaning in Gemara: “Now” [that you’ve told me] X, [how can it be that] Y. So, when we see this type of השתא, we’re expecting it to be followed by 1. a fact we just learned, and 2. something else that is now confusing in light of that fact.
2) We should recognize the words בו, בשלוחו, and מקדש from the Mishnah. When words or phrases from the Mishnah appear in the Gemara, they are often quotations.
3) When the word מיבעיא _meboya_ is used regarding the Mishnah, it is often used to state or ask why the author of the Mishnah “needed” to include something in the Mishnah.
4) Because the Gemara doesn’t have question marks, a statement without an explanation is often actually a question.
Putting that all together, the Gemara reads: “Now [that the Mishnah told me] _“b’shlucho mekadesh”_ i.e. that he can be _mekadesh_ with his _shaliach_, _“bo”_ i.e. that he can do it with himself, is needed [to be taught]?”
