אמר רב יוסף מצוה בו יותר מבשלוחו:
< <gray>גמ’ השתא בשלוחו מקדש בו מיבעיא</gray> אמר
< רב יוסף מצוה בו יותר מבשלוחו<gray> כי הא דרב
< ספרא מחריך רישא רבא מלח שיבוטא</gray>
The Gemara just asked why the Mishnah needs to tell me a man can be mekadesh בו, himself, when I can infer that from he can do it בשלוחו, with his _shaliach_.
Now, we’re expecting an answer to the question.
The words אמר רב יוסף, _amar Rav Yosef_ are the standard introduction to a statement of an Amora.
The words מצוה בו יותר מבשלוחו literally translate to “_mitzvah_ with himself more than with his _shaliach_.”
So, we had been expecting a reason the Tana would tell us explicitly he can do it himself when I can infer that from that he can do it with his _shaliach_, and the answer is “_mitzvah_ with himself more than with his _shaliach_.”
So it sounds like R Yosef holds that the Tana included the word בו because of a principle called “it’s a bigger mitzvah to do it yourself than with a _shaliach_.”
We’ll have to understand the exact mechanics of what he’s suggesting.
===
> [[^]]
===

כי הא דרב ספרא מחריך רישא רבא מלח שיבוטא:
< <gray>גמ’ השתא בשלוחו מקדש בו מיבעיא אמר
< רב יוסף מצוה בו יותר מבשלוחו</gray> כי הא דרב
< ספרא מחריך רישא רבא מלח שיבוטא<gray>
< איכא דאמרי בהא איסורא נמי אית בה</gray>
We just heard R Yosef’s answer to the Gemara’s question, that the Tana included בו to teach a principle called _mitzvah yoser m’b’shlucho_.
Now the Gemara says כי הא דרב ספרא, “like that of R Safra,” which sounds like we’re introducing a teaching or story from R Safra.
We can tell this is the Gemara speaking and not more from R Yosef because these Amoriam mentioned are after his time.
The two examples mentioned, R Safra singed the head i.e. of an animal, Rava salted something called a _shibuta_ sound like Amoriam being particular to participate in preparing for Shabbos themselves.
This would be an example of R Yosef’s principle, that it is “more” of a _mitzvah_ to do something yourself than to do it via another person.
