איכא דאמרי:
< <gray>ספרא מחריך רישא רבא מלח שיבוטא</gray>
< איכא דאמרי <gray> בהא איסורא נמי אית בה</gray>
The words איכא דאמרי literally mean “there is/are” “that [they] say” i.e. “there are those who say.”
This phrase has a technical meaning in Gemara, that some Amora involved the composition of the Gemara had two versions of a given Talmudic discussion, and now we’re going to see the second one.
Sometimes איכא דאמרי introduces a new version of the same discussion between the same people previously mentioned.
Sometimes it introduces a different discussion of the same question that occured in a different place, unknown to the participants in the first discussion and vice versa.
Either way, it differs from a conventional Talmudic debate e.g. _amar Rava_ vs. _amar Abaye_ because the term _amar_ more strongly implies that the people mentioned or their students were arguing directly with one another in the same place, rather than איכא דאמרי which implies two traditions that developed separately.
===
> [[^]]
===

בהא איסורא נמי אית בה:
< <gray>ספרא מחריך רישא רבא מלח שיבוטא</gray>
< <gray>איכא דאמרי</gray> בהא איסורא נמי אית בה
< <gray>כדרב יהודה אמר רב דאמר רב יהודה</gray>
When we have an איכא דאמרי introducing a new version of the prior Gemara, the Gemara will usually for brevity only mention the part of the new version that diverges from the old one.
However, it isn’t always clear at what point the two diverge. For example, the איכא דאמרי could be replacing the most recent statement, or, it could be a different version of the very first statement, etc.
So, to know how to reconstruct the new version of the Gemara, we will need to try inserting this new line periodically at each point in the existing version, and see at which point it makes sense.
Our Gemara begins by asking _hashta b’shlucho mekadesh bo meboya_, now that the Mishnah has told me בשלוחו, why does it need to tell me בו? Perhaps this line is an alternative question on our Mishnah. However, the words “in this there is an _issur_” don’t really make sense as a question on the Mishnah.
So, our Gemara first offers the answer of R Yosef, that the בו is to teach you it is more of a _mitzvah_ to do something yourself. Perhaps the איכא דאמרי is offering an alternative answer to the Gemara’s question. If so, then whereas R Yosef thinks the בו is to teach that something is a bigger _mitzvah_, this new answer is claiming that it is to teach that something is _nami issura_, also _assur_. We don’t have full clarity yet what this answer entails, but at least we see that this new line fits as an alternative to R Yosef’s answer.
So, this new version of the Gemara may have began with our same Mishnah, asked the same question _hashta b’shlucho mekadesh bo meboya_, and offered this answer instead of R Yosef’s.
===
> [[^]]
===

