כדרב יהודה אמר רב דאמר רב יהודה אמר רב:
< <gray>איכא דאמרי בהא איסורא נמי אית בה</gray>
< כדרב יהודה אמר רב דאמר רב יהודה
< אמר רב<gray> אסור לאדם שיקדש את האשה</gray>
The words כדרב יהודה אמר רב literally mean “like of Rav Yehuda said Rav.”
The Gemara had just suggested that the extra בו in the Mishnah was to implicitly teach the requirement of seeing a woman before _kiddushin_.
Now, the Gemara is continuing that if so, this teaching would be *“like”* this other later teaching we’ve heard explicitly.
The ד which can mean “of” can also mean “[that] of,” and so כד “like of” would really mean “like that of” i.e. “like that teaching of” R Yehuda _amar_ Rav.
The phrase רב יהודה אמר רב, R Yehuda amar Rav generally implies that R Yehuda heard the teaching directly from Rav.
