וכי איתמר דרב יוסף אסיפא איתמר האשה מתקדשת בה ובשלוחה:
< <gray>כמוך </gray>וכי איתמר דרב יוסף אסיפא איתמר
< האשה מתקדשת בה ובשלוחה <gray>השתא</gray>
The word כי can mean a lot of things but here it seems to mean “when,” and so וכי, _v’chi_, “and when.”
The word איתמר _itmar_ is a passive verb meaning “[it] was said.”
So וכי איתמר, _v’chi itmar_, “and when [it] was said.”
The phrase דרב יוסף, _d’Rav Yosef_ means “of R Yosef,” but ד can also mean “[that thing] of,” so here, “[that statement] of R Yosef.”
The phrase אסיפא איתמר means אסיפא, _a’seifa_, “on/regarding the end/bottom” איתמר, _itmar_, it was said. The Mishnah had three clauses, so you might think the _seifa_ should be the third, but we’ll see that the Gemara means the second, and some Rishonim will use the phrase _seifa d’seifa_, “bottom of the bottom” to refer to the third clause.
In the original version of the Gemara, R Yosef brought the extra בו in the first clause of the Mishnah as his evidence, and now we’re saying in the new version he is bringing the extra בה in the second clause as his evidence.
And then Gemara provides us a quote of this second clause, האשה מתקדשת בה ובשלוחה, _ha’isha miskadeshes ba u’b’shluchah_, a woman can become _mekudeshes_ בה via herself or בשלוחה via her shaliach, with now the בה being extra.
So וכי איתמר דרב יוסף אסיפא איתמר, _v’chi itmar d’Rav Yosef a’seifa itmar_, “and when was said that statement of R Yosef, regarding the seifa [i.e. second clause of the Mishnah] it was said,” האשה מתקדשת בה ובשלוחה, _ha’isha miskadeshes ba u’b’shluchah_, a woman can become _mekudeshes_ via herself or via her _shaliach_.
