< למיתב טן דו מלמיתב ארמלו: האיש</gray>
The abbreviation כדר״ל, short for כדריש לקיש, means “like/as, of/for, Reish Lakesh.”
This is a common expression for stating a source for a halachic statement, i.e. “as [we see in the statement] of Reish Lakesh.”
===
> [[^]]
===

טב למיתב טן דו מלמיתב ארמלו:
< <gray>איסורא לית בה כדר״ל דאמר ר״ל</gray> טב
< למיתב טן דו מלמיתב ארמלו: <gray>האיש</gray>
The word טב, _tav_, seems to be an Aramaic permuation of the Hebrew טוב. The word למיתב, _l’masiv_, means to sit or to live. Put together, טב למיתב, _tav l’masiv_, means “good to sit.”
The word טן _tan_, seems to be an uncommon word meaning “in grief.” The word דו _du_, seems to be an uncommon word meaning “two,” perhaps similar to the word “duo.” Put together, טב למיתב טן דו, _tav l’masiv tan du_, means “good to sit grieved together.”
Now, the next word מלמיתב begins with a מ prefix which usually means “from.” The rest of the word למיתב, _l’masiv_, we saw earlier means “to sit/live.” So that would mean that מלמיתב, _m’l’masiv_ means “from to sit/live” which doesn’t make sense.
But, מ has a second meaning which is “than,” which can only occur if we were already in the middle of a comparison, which, maybe we were!
So, now we would backtrack and see that טב _tav_, which would generally mean “good” in this context could mean “_better_, [one thing]” and this later מ means “_than_ [something else]”
So, Reish Lakesh comes out _tav l’masiv tan du m’l’masiv armalo_, better to sit/live grieved together than to sit/live as a widow.
Later we will clarify the meaning of this saying, and how it relates practically to our sugya.
